<section class="card">
  <h2>What Gold Rush Is Best For</h2>

  <p>
    Gold Rush is best for gardeners who want russet-type potatoes for baking, cooking, and storage.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is not the earliest new-potato choice. Give it time to size and set skins if storage is the goal.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Is Gold Rush Good for Short Seasons?</h2>

  <p>
    Potatoes can work well in short seasons because they are planted before tender summer crops and can be harvested as new potatoes before full maturity.
  </p>

  <p>
    For storage potatoes, the crop needs enough time for vines to grow, tubers to size, and skins to set before harvest.
  </p>

  <p>
    Variety maturity matters, but soil conditions, seed quality, and water consistency matter just as much.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>When to Plant Gold Rush</h2>

  <p>
    Plant seed potatoes in spring once soil can be worked and is not cold and waterlogged. Potatoes tolerate cool weather, but poor soil conditions can rot seed pieces.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short seasons, plant early enough for full-size tubers while still avoiding saturated soil.
  </p>

  <p>
    For local timing, use the <a href="https://growbydate.com/crops/potato/">potato growing guide</a> and your frost dates. Storage potatoes need time to mature before cold, wet harvest weather.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How to Grow Gold Rush</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Use certified seed potatoes:</strong> Good seed reduces disease risk and improves stand quality.</li>
    <li><strong>Plant in workable soil:</strong> Cold soggy soil can rot seed pieces.</li>
    <li><strong>Hill plants:</strong> Hilling protects developing tubers from light and supports more covered stem.</li>
    <li><strong>Water during tuber set:</strong> Dry stress can reduce yield and tuber quality.</li>
    <li><strong>Avoid greening:</strong> Keep tubers covered so they are not exposed to sunlight.</li>
    <li><strong>Let skins set for storage:</strong> Storage potatoes keep better after vines die back and skins toughen.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Harvest and Storage</h2>

  <p>
    Dig new potatoes when plants are flowering or when small tubers are large enough to use. For storage, wait until vines die back and skins have set.
  </p>

  <p>
    Harvest gently to avoid bruising or cutting tubers. Damaged potatoes should be used first.
  </p>

  <p>
    Cure storage potatoes in a dark, ventilated place, then keep them cool, dark, and humid. Do not store green or damaged tubers.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Growing Gold Rush</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Planting into wet cold soil:</strong> Seed pieces can rot before plants establish.</li>
    <li><strong>Letting tubers see light:</strong> Sun-exposed tubers turn green and should not be eaten.</li>
    <li><strong>Skipping hilling:</strong> Uncovered tubers are more likely to green.</li>
    <li><strong>Harvesting storage potatoes too early:</strong> Thin skins reduce storage life.</li>
    <li><strong>Handling tubers roughly:</strong> Bruises and cuts shorten storage.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Gold Rush vs Other Potato Varieties</h2>

  <p>
    Compared with other potato varieties, Gold Rush should be judged by maturity class, cooking use, yield, and storage potential. Early potatoes and storage potatoes are often grown for different reasons.
  </p>

  <p>
    For this crop, the better choice depends on what you want from the harvest. Gold Rush is worth growing when its maturity window, plant habit, and kitchen use match your garden better than a faster, larger, or more specialized alternative.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Who Should Grow Gold Rush?</h2>

  <p>
    Gold Rush is a good choice if you want a practical potato crop and can give it loose soil, steady moisture, and enough time to size tubers.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is less satisfying when planted late for storage or grown in compacted soil where tubers cannot develop cleanly.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Plan Around Your Local Season</h2>

  <p>
    Gold Rush can be a good choice when the timing matches your spring conditions, growing season length, and expected fall frost. The exact planting window still depends on where you garden.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before choosing a planting date, check your local frost window and crop timing. A variety can fit short seasons well and still underperform if it is planted too late, started too late indoors, or grown in poor conditions.
